---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
	title="Coverage & Antennas"
	description="Learn how LoRa mesh coverage works in Madison, how to maximize your node's range, and which antennas to use."
>
	<div class="container">
		<!-- How LoRa coverage works -->
		<section class="section">
			<h1>Coverage &amp; Antennas</h1>
			<p>
				LoRa uses a spread-spectrum modulation technique on the 915 MHz ISM band (in North America) that
				allows signals to reach much further than Wi-Fi or Bluetooth. In ideal conditions, a node placed in
				an elevated location can span <strong>10+ miles</strong>. However, a node sitting on a desk indoors
				may only reach a few blocks.
				<br />
				<br />
			</p>

			<h2>The following factors affect LoRa coverage:</h2>
			<div class="card-grid">
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Line of Sight</h3>
					<p>
						LoRa performs best when there's an unobstructed path between nodes. Hills, buildings, and
						dense trees all reduce range. Even a few feet of extra elevation can dramatically improve
						coverage.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Urban Environments</h3>
					<p>
						In a city like Madison, buildings degrade range significantly. Most nodes can reliably
						reach 0.5–3 miles urban, or 2–10 miles from a rooftop or elevated location.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Mesh Relaying</h3>
					<p>
						The power of mesh is that each node forwards messages for others. Even if two nodes can't
						see each other directly, they can communicate through intermediate nodes in the network.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Weather &amp; Season</h3>
					<p>
						LoRa range is relatively immune to rain but Wisconsin's terrain and foliage density in
						summer can reduce effective range. Winter (bare trees) often improves coverage noticeably.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Madison-specific notes -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Coverage in the Madison Area</h2>
			<p>
				Madison's geography is challenging for mesh networking. The isthmus between the two lakes creates
				natural elevation gradients, and the surrounding hills and bluffs tend to block line of sight.
				However, strategic node placement can still provide robust coverage across large portions of the
				city from a single location.
			</p>
		</section>
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Node Placement Tips</h2>
			<div class="steps">
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">1</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Height is might</h3>
						<p>
							Nodes placed on HAM towers, rooftops, or in upper-floor windows dramatically
							outperform ground-level placements. Even getting above the treeline makes a
							meaningful difference. If you can see the Capitol dome from your location, you likely
							have excellent coverage potential.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">2</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Look for gaps in coverage</h3>
						<p>
							Currently the network is thinner on Madison's west and east sides, and in many
							surrounding towns. If you're in Fitchburg, Monona, Middleton, Sun Prairie, or Verona
							— you're in a great position to add needed coverage.
							<a href="https://msn.meshmapper.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
								>Check the map</a
							>
							to see the current MeshCore network coverage.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Antennas -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Choosing an Antenna</h2>
			<p>
				The stock antenna that comes with most LoRa radios is adequate for portable use but a significant
				upgrade is available for fixed nodes. Here are the main types:
			</p>

			<div class="card-grid card-grid-wide">
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Stock Stub/PCB Antenna</h3>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">&le;2 dBi gain</p>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem;">
						The small antenna included with most radios. Convenient for testing to see if nodes are
						nearby. <strong>Generally not recommended</strong> — replace with any of the options below.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Whip / Fiberglass Omni</h3>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">3–6 dBi gain</p>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem;">
						A good general-purpose upgrade. Sends signal in all horizontal directions equally. Great
						for nodes that need to connect to neighbors on multiple sides. Look for N-type or
						SMA-connector models designed for 915 MHz.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>High-gain Fiberglass</h3>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">8–15+ dBi gain</p>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem;">
						Focuses signal out to the sides in a "flat donut" shape. Covers long distances better, but
						less effective for nearby nodes or those in the direction of the nulls (above and below).
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Yagi / Directional</h3>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">8–15+ dBi gain</p>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem;">
						Focuses signal in one direction. Very useful for long-distance point-to-point links (e.g.,
						bridging between neighborhoods), but less helpful for the broader mesh.
						<br />
						<br />
						<i
							>Some users in distant locations have had success using a directional antenna pointed
							towards other nodes, and then a second node nearby with an omni antenna to relay
							messages closer to home.</i
						>
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div
				class="card"
				style="margin-top: 1.5rem; background-color: oklch(22% 0.06 232.69); border-color: var(--clr-primary-darker);"
			>
				<h3 style="color: var(--clr-primary);">Quick upgrade recommendation</h3>
				<p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
					For most users, spending $10-20 on a <strong>3–5 dBi 915 MHz omni antenna</strong> is a great choice.
					The <a
						href="https://muzi.works/products/whip-antenna-17cm"
						target="_blank"
						rel="noopener noreferrer">Muzi 17cm whip</a
					> is a popular option for mobile nodes, and the
					<a
						href="https://store.rokland.com/products/alfa-aoa-915-5acm-5-dbi-omni-outdoor-915mhz-802-11ah-mini-antenna-for-lora-halow-application"
						target="_blank"
						rel="noopener noreferrer">Alfa 5dBi Omni</a
					> is best for fixed outdoor nodes.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Antenna cables and connectors -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Cables, Adapters &amp; Placement</h2>

			<div class="steps">
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">1</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Keep coax cable short</h3>
						<p>
							RF signal is lost in coax cable. Use the shortest cable possible — ideally under 10
							inches for low-cost RG174/RG316 coax. RG-58 is good for slightly longer runs. Try to
							avoid runs over 3 feet, and try to use higher-quality LMR-200 or LMR-400 cable in
							those scenarios. <strong
								>Strongly consider mounting the radio close to the antenna and using a long
								USB/power cable whenever possible.</strong
							>
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">2</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Common connectors</h3>
						<p>
							Most small LoRa boards use <strong>U.FL / IPEX</strong> connectors. Many outdoor fiberglass
							antennas terminate in <strong>N-type</strong>. Be sure to check your specific radio's
							connector type before buying an antenna or pigtail, and pay special attention to
							avoid buying RP-SMA connectors when you need SMA.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">3</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Interior vs. exterior</h3>
						<p>
							A node inside a window loses some signal through the glass and frame. An antenna
							mounted outside on a pole or eave is always better. If running a cable outside is not
							possible, place the node in the highest window facing the most open direction.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<section class="section">
			<h2>Want help with your setup?</h2>
			<p>
				Coverage and RF questions are a common topic in our Discord. Members can help with antenna
				selection, placement ideas, and tell you whether existing nodes are likely in range of your
				location.
			</p>
			<a
				href="https://discord.gg/fd3JUZc2CN"
				target="_blank"
				rel="noopener noreferrer"
				class="btn btn-primary"
			>
				Ask in Discord &rarr;
			</a>
		</section>
	</div>
</Layout>
